                                <foliation>Modern foliation in pencil, 1-79, 78-79 (repeated), 80-123 (<locus from="54A" to="54A" scheme="folios"/> not foliated). <locus from="2r" to="114r" scheme="folios"/>, older foliation in ink, 8-123, partly trimmed in places and crossed out in pencil. The foliation continues in pencil on <locus from="115r" to="115r" scheme="folios"/>, 124-132, also crossed out. <secFol>iusta Cum exarserit</secFol>
                                </foliation>
                                <collation>
                                    <p>The manuscript is too fragile to be fully collated. However, as the textblock is more or less entirely detached from the binding, the quires, sixteen in all, can be counted at the spine. The first six quires have catchwords at intervals of 8 leaves, indicating an overall structure of quaternions.</p>
                                    <catchwords>Catchwords on quires 1-6.</catchwords>
                                </collation>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner, in brown ink by an early modern hand: <quote>N<hi rend="super">o</hi> 10</quote>; below: <quote>Brocmanni</quote>; top centre, in brown ink in Brocman's hand, a note identifying the elevation of the feast of St George to <foreign xml:lang="la">festum duplex</foreign> in November 1415: <quote>MCCCCXV in nov. Festivitas S. Georgii mart. ut duplex festum celebretur Stat. Seld. Tit. Hon. p. 574 ed. lat.</quote> Bottom of page, in brown ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Hunc librum dono mihi dedit pater carissimus <gap quantity="7" unit="chars" reason="damage"/>.</quote>
                                    <!--Skulle vilja identifiera referensen. Ej hittat. Men lägga in typ dictionay of National Biography?-->
                                </note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="false">
                                <p>Early modern binding. White leather over cardboard. 3 raised bands and endbands, with the fastenings visible on the outside of the covers at the spine. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, in ink, barly legible: <quote>N<hi rend="super">o</hi> 10 Brocm</quote>; stamped in gold: <quote>A 182</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
